		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Death of a Game<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.64)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4995'>James-Jason "Duo337" Wade</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4995&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 2, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> What brings about the end of a game and what makes people not want to play a game anymore? In this article I hope to express my concerns as a former card player of LOTR, SWCCG, and Magic in order to give advice on the future.<br />
<br />
****************WARNING! WARNING! WARNING!*****************<br />
THIS CONTAINS MANY OPINIONS AND OBSERVATIONS THAT MANY WILL SEE AS FALSE OR JUST A LIE, BUT LET IT BE KNOWN! THESE ARE NOTHING MORE THEN 5 YEARS OF GAMING EXPERIENCE SEEN THOUGH THE EYES OF A SIMPLE ALABAMA SCHOOL BOY! ANY OTHER IDEAS OR REMARKS ABOUT WHAT THIS MEANS CANNOT BE  IDENTIFIED WITHOUT TALKING TO ME ABOUT WHAT I HAVE SEEN!<br />
<br />
IN THE BEGINNING! Their was an idea, movie, or a system that was developed. It takes a lot of hard work and motivation to bring this new game into existence. In order to design the cards themselves, all the different operations they can perform, the different &quot;moves&quot; they can make, how the game can be played, the basic rules behind the game, and all the way up to the printing of the cards are all needed to make a game possible. Of course, what game could exist without someone to play it right? The people who buy the game and play it expect to get their moneys worth out of the game from the time they pick up the box and play it to the time they put it back for whatever reasons they wish to own the cards. When a company or person decides to design a card game, they must also choose a target base for their customers (example: Yu-Gi-Oh younger ages 11-14, Star wars older ages 15+). Most of these card games always start out big and everyone loves to play them over and over again. I remember when LOTR came out in Huntsville everyone played it non-stop and didn&#39;t seem to care about Star Wars at all anymore! I admit, it was a grand game when it started and I played it a lot as well. But the after effects of this new game slowly showed itself to everyone with myself being no exception. This showed me how tragic of a loss a game can be when the players are no longer looked as people trying to have fun but rather people to exploit for profit.<br />
<br />
What brings about the end of a game. Technically a game will never die as long as players wish to play it. But, in due respect, I believe we all agree on what a dead game or dying game is, was, or will be shortly. When a card company/the maker of a game refuses to print anymore of a game or continue to sell new versions is when a game officially dies. Shortly after players will lose interest and the game will slowly fade away into nothingness. Is this really the case? Or is it possible that a company can continue to print off versions of a game while many within the gaming community consider it a dead game? We have all seen the finial days of the SWCCG when decipher was shooting off a new expansion seemingly every month. It came as a serious blow to me when I found out that decipher, one way or another, lost the license to star wars and that no new cards would be made. Despite this, I continued to play the game with the new SWCCG players committee making new cards for the game by revising the text of old cards. But even with this I lost interest with the game to a point were I was sadden every time I looked at my mounds of cards in the corner of my downstairs living room. What had happened? Simple, when the idea of a fun game is taken away in favor of greed and profit for the betterment of the maker. Pumping out a new expansion every few months took away from the fun of the game by making it nearly impossible to keep up both competitively and by just having a good time. This combined with many players needs to prove how smart they are thought these games made it extremely difficult to find someone who was willing to play just for fun.<br />
<br />
What makes people not want to play a game anymore? For me, it was when I realized that people in my area that played this game did it, only to prove that they themselves was better then another person. I saw first hand how this works. Greed and pride overtake the idea of having fun. The game turns into a competition into who is better then the other person. The biggest slap in the face came about two years ago. These two brothers, as I later found out, were very good at card games and had solid decks within the STCCG (1st edition) and LOTR area at the respectable time. I was paired against one in a LOTR game, he seemed nice to me though out the entire game but hardly said anything. At the end when he had won, I reached to shake his hand and said &quot;good game&quot; to him while smiling. He said &quot;yea whatever&quot; and continued on his way. Later, as I find out, he was joking on my deck as I was playing dwarfs in the local tournament area. I really didn&#39;t think much of it until I found out that he played in STCCG tournaments and he ended up winning that day. I found out that as soon as he got his prize foil he also popped it on e-bay ASAP for no less then 50$. This baffled me. As the weeks progressed I learned why he played the game. He played it to sell the cards to people on-line and made the best decks possible just to win. Not a terribly bad idea to most, but his attitude is what struck me as the worst thing. My good friend Andy McClure, who was great at the game of Star Wars, did the same thing but tended to have fun with it all and I laughed and enjoyed playing him always. No, the day I finally said this is enough is when I ended up beating him for the second week in a row and he said &quot;even losers get lucky&quot;. From that point on, I stopped looking at this as a game but rather as an object of obsession for people to prove themselves. A year later, the competition from this had grow and grow to a point were nobody smiled when they played anymore. Our local regular crowd went from 30 people to just 10 in a year. By 2003, LOTR tourneys were all but legend in our area. Too many people were temped by &quot;fame&quot; and money won by these things to care about what really mattered... that it was a game. A friend and fellow gamer said to me something rather interesting. While him and others were trying to prove themselves better though the game, I had continued to play both LOTR and SWCCG just for the sole reason of having fun. Needless to say, he was on to something.<br />
<br />
When a game stops becoming just a game to people, what does it turn into? When I heard about a new Marvel game coming out, I was very temped to buy into it so I could play with my fellow gamers again. But upon hearing about the grand prize at the tourneys, my heart flickered. I said to myself &quot;History can easily repeat itself&quot;. With that, I forced myself to sell off all my cards in order to not draw myself into that cycle of greed and thinking that I am better then another because I am able to beat them at a silly card game. Some people argue that completion is what drives these games and makes them so great. This CAN be true, but when the fun is taken out for the betterment of making money. It is no longer a game, thus a game will die. I have seen LOTR and SWCCG pass into darkness in my area. Not because they were bad games, but because the people who played them took the games to a level in which I could not comprehend. A level to were the game is more business then a game. This is the main reason why so many games can die so fast. When people don&#39;t like the games, but rather use them to get money and other things. This is the truth. Why people who play games are the main reason they succeed, and the main reason why they fail. <br />
<br />
Consider this article more words for the wise, and warnings to new players. For those who disagree with what I have seen, then I am sorry for your situation.<br />
<br />
Good day decktech!<br />
Jason, aka Da_wade, of Huntsville. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=5566&view=1&PHPSESSID=bd35f1af14759147cd8ee86081c4668b'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=bd35f1af14759147cd8ee86081c4668b'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=bd35f1af14759147cd8ee86081c4668b'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
